page.title: 02THE RIVER WYE
page.content: High Wycombe was built on the{River {Wye}to which it owes it's name.{Combe meant{valley}in old English, so WY-COMBE means "the valley of the River Wye". The river,which is nine miles long, flows from West Wycombe, through the town and into the River Thames at Bourne End. Formerly, it provided power for the{40 water mills along its banks for grinding corn, fulling wool, and making paper. It was also known for its trout. In 1970,the river was diverted underground for half a mile in the town centre in order to build a relief road and the Octogon shopping centre. It emerges at the southern end of St Mary's Street. There are now few fish in the Wye,and it no longer provides power for industry,but it attracts picnickers and anglers to its banks.
